Yes, the document allows the Receiving Party to share some Confidential Information with their employees, referred to as "Representatives," under specific conditions. According to clause 2.2, the Receiving Party may disclose the Disclosing Party's Confidential Information to its Representatives who need to know this information for the Purpose, provided that:

(a) The Receiving Party informs its Representatives of the confidential nature of the Confidential Information before disclosure;

(b) The Receiving Party ensures that its Representatives comply with the Agreement as if they were the Receiving Party, and if requested by the Disclosing Party, the Receiving Party must procure that any relevant Representative enters into a confidentiality agreement with the Disclosing Party on terms equivalent to those in this Agreement;

(c) The Receiving Party keeps a written record of these Representatives;

Additionally, the Receiving Party must not disclose the Confidential Information to any third party except as expressly permitted by the Agreement, and must not copy or record the Confidential Information except as strictly necessary for the Purpose. 

These conditions ensure that the Confidential Information is protected even when shared with employees.
